[[Towards Wallet Solutions in Web3]]


- Step 1:What is a Wallet?
    
    A wallet is basically a store that contains public and private keys to give access to digital assets in the blockchain. It is a solution that allows users to interact in the blockchain securely.
    
    A public and a private key that are related and dependent on each other is called a key-pair.
    
    Your public key is akin to your public address that allows others to send you digital assets to your account. Your private key allows access to your digital assets and allows you to send transactions to other users. The diagram below shows a simplification of such interaction.
    
    ![](data:image/png;base64,)
    
    Keep in mind to hide your wallets from anyone, especially your private keys.
    
- Step 2:Private Keys and Digital Asset Access
    
    **Remember that digital assets are stored on the blockchain and not from a wallet**. _Your wallet is just the key to accessing your digital assets much like a key to a vault_.
    
    **When accessing digital assets**, it only needs the private key. Losing the public key is not the end of the world as long as you have access to your private keys. The diagram below explains two situations:
    
    - User 1 has access to their private key
    - User 2 has no access to their private key
    
    ![](data:image/png;base64,)
    
    Be careful when losing your private keys because losing them means losing access to your digital assets. The digital assets are not deleted or removed in the blockchain. They’re just inaccessible to anyone that has no idea about your private key.
    
    Fortunately, there is a way to access again your wallet and keys. It will be discussed in the next step.
    
- Step 3:Seed Phrases
    
    To solve issues when losing private keys, a **seed phrase** is provided to access your private keys which means you now have access to your digital assets.
    
    **A seed phrase** is a _collection of random words that serve as the passphrase of your wallet_.
    
    It's important to note that seed phrases and private keys are different.
    
    - A seed phrase gives access to your private keys.
    - Private keys give access to your digital assets on the blockchain.
    - Knowing the seed phrase, therefore, gives access to your digital assets.
    
    However, **both of them should be stored somewhere safe away from prying eyes**.
    
    **It’s recommended to have both the seed phrase and the private key around just in case.**
    
    The diagram below shows a flowchart if a user loses their private key but might still know their seed phrase
    
    ![](data:image/png;base64,)
    
- Step 4:Importance of Private Keys and Seed Phrases
    
    It is also important to note that if an untrusted third-party knows your private keys, that also means they also have full access to your digital assets.
    
    Even knowing the seed phrase to your private keys is enough to give access.
    
    Once an untrusted third-party also has access to both your private key and your public key, **they can impersonate you** and use your public key to receive funds.
    
    Fortunately, getting your seed phrase or private key is hard. The time it takes to get your information takes billions of years, statistically. The usual ways of getting hacked are misplaced keys or phishing links or accidentally showing your private keys to the public.
    
- Step 5:Cold Wallets vs Hot Wallets
    
    Let’s talk about types of wallets. Let’s begin with cold wallets.
    
    ## Cold Wallets
    
    Cold wallets are wallets that store private and public keys offline. This type of wallet requires physical access to a device. A good example of a cold wallet provider which is usually referred as a hardware wallet is [Ledger](https://www.ledger.com/). They look similar to USB thumbdrives. This type of wallet still requires a computer to connect the wallet to the internet. **The advantage is that the private keys are stored in the cold wallet**. When signing transactions, the software installed in the cold wallet **performs the signing using the private key** stored in the wallet as long as it is plugged into a computer.
    
    The **disadvantage of using a cold wallet**, however, is it is limited on the physical store. Since cold wallets exist as a tangible object, a disaster such as a fire or putting the cold wallets at the wrong place at the wrong time means losing access to your private keys or seed phrases which means losing access to all of your digital assets on the blockchain.
    
    But even if you misplace or lose your hardware wallet, you can get a new one and **if you still remember your Secret Recovery Phrase**, you can still have access to your assets and your private and public keys.
    
    ![](data:image/png;base64,)
    
    ## Hot Wallets
    
    Wallets that are **always connected to a network** are called “Hot” wallets. Hot wallets, unlike cold wallets, are almost always connected to the internet. They either serve as an intermediary to connect cold wallets to the network or can act as standalone wallets - the former still performs the signing in the cold wallet while the latter **performs the signing using the private key stored in the hot wallet**.  
    
    However, hot wallets are more vulnerable to third-party online access unlike cold wallets.
    
    Nevertheless, as mentioned before, getting your seed phrase or private key is hard. The time it takes to get your information takes billions of years, statistically.
    
    ![](data:image/png;base64,)
    
    The usual ways of getting hacked are misplaced keys or phishing links or accidentally showing your private keys to the public.
    
    The **two diagrams** below differentiates the usage between hot and cold wallets.

- Step 6:Non-Exhaustive List of EVM-compatible Wallets
    
    Congratulations! You now have some basic knowledge about wallets such as how they work, how to secure your wallet and the basic security features of wallets. Now let’s take a look at some wallet providers in this step.
    
    Now here is a question, why are there different wallet providers? What are they trying to solve?
    
    For these questions, feel free to discuss this on the StackUp Discord! These discussions are really important for you and for others. By discussing these issues and listening to problems, we can also think of solutions that will solve those problems.
    
    Now let’s proceed and take a look at some wallet providers in this step.
    
    Here is a non-exhaustive list of EVM-compatible wallets
    
    - [Rabby Wallet](https://rabby.io/)
    - [Rainbow](https://rainbow.me/en-us/)
    - [Metamask](https://metamask.io/)
    
    Metamask is the most popular out of the list of EVM-compatible wallets. Rainbow and Rabby are other EVM-compatible wallets.
    
    Metamask has browser extensions for Firefox and Chromium-based browsers such as Chrome and Opera. It also has a mobile app for Android and iOS.
    
    Rainbow Wallet has browser extensions for Firefox and Chromium-based browsers. It also has a mobile app for Android and iOS.
    
    Rabby has a desktop app for Windows and MacOS. The browser extension only lists Chrome browser but do note that this might also mean it can support Chromium-based browsers such as Edge and Brave.  
    
    Rabby also has a mobile app in Beta for Android and iOS.
    
    ⚠️ For other wallets not mentioned above, it's best to research about them first before trying them out! A good start would be visiting [https://www.alchemy.com/list-of/software-wallets-on-ethereum](https://www.alchemy.com/list-of/software-wallets-on-ethereum).
    
    Although there are many existing wallet solutions, **most of them are usually just UI and UX improvements with additional features**. In the next step, the common but important security features will be discussed.
    
- Step 7:Other Wallets
    
    We already have mentioned EVM-compatible wallets. However, Ethereum is not the only blockchain network. EVM-compatible wallets include Polygon and Arbitrum. Wallets for non-EVM-compatible networks such [Solana](https://solana.com/) and [Cosmos](https://cosmos.network/) exist as well. The following are a non-exhaustive list of these wallets
    
    Solana-compatible wallets are
    
    - [Phantom](https://phantom.app/)
    - [Torus](https://app.tor.us/)
    
    Cosmos-compatible wallets are
    
    - [Keplr](https://www.kepler.app/)
    - [Leap](https://www.leapwallet.io/)
    
    When using or choosing a wallet, always remember to take note which wallets are for which blockchain. Although, some wallets do offer multi-blockchain support, it’s best to use a wallet that are specialised for your use cases.
    
    In the next step, we will look forward to learn more about how to transact using wallets.
    
- Step 8:Testnet Faucets
    
    Before we begin using wallets, let us have a short discussion about faucets and testnets.
    
    A faucet dispenses free tokens on a testnet. This allows users to simulate their transactions.
    
    Before doing transactions, it is best to simulate transactions before doing any real transactions using a free testnet faucet.
    
    The advantage of using faucets and testnets is to avoid the risk and mistakes when transacting and also in Web3 development.
    
    Once you are ready to use your wallets, you can switch to a mainnet where you will actually do the real transactions.
    
    In the following steps, we will use [Rainbow](https://rainbow.me/) as the wallet. Feel free to use any wallet and make your own opinions on which is your preferred wallet.
